{"id":"thm:tie-local-separation-obstruction","kind":"theorem","statement":"The frozen assumptions do not imply a uniform root-\(n\) local-power conclusion over positive-mass ties. More precisely, they admit the canonical tie subexperiment in \(\textup{lem:tie-subexperiment-minimax-boundary}\), on which, with \(r_n=n^{-2\beta/(4\beta+d)}\), every sequence of tests \(\varphi_n\) satisfying \[\sup_{P:C_P(0,0)=0}E_P[\varphi_n]\le\alpha+o(1)\]has worst-case power at most \(\alpha+\eta+o(1)\) against some alternatives with \(C_P(0,0)\asymp r_n\), for every \(\eta>0\). There are also alternatives with \(C_P(0,0)\asymp n^{-1/2}\) for which the power is at most \(\alpha+o(1)\). The rate \(r_n\) is sharp in that subexperiment: the explicit quadratic projection test in \(\textup{lem:tie-subexperiment-minimax-boundary}\) is consistent whenever \(C_P(0,0)/r_n\to\infty\). By contrast, on the fixed constant-shift paths of \(\textup{lem:regular-constant-path-power}\), root-\(n\) separation is regular and the two-sided local power is \[1-\Phi\!\left(z_{1-\alpha/2}-\frac{\kappa}{\sqrt{2}(b-a)}\right)+\Phi\!\left(-z_{1-\alpha/2}-\frac{\kappa}{\sqrt{2}(b-a)}\right).\]Consequently, no uniformly valid test, including an inversion of the frozen numerical directional-delta procedure if it has the claimed level, can have a nontrivial worst-case power curve indexed only by \(\sqrt n C_P(\theta)\) over the tie-inclusive primitive class. The frozen conditions therefore answer the local-power part negatively: the regular pointwise boundary is \(n^{-1/2}\), whereas the uniform positive-mass-tie boundary can be \(n^{-2\beta/(4\beta+d)}\). This theorem neither proves nor refutes the coverage claim for \(\widehat{\mathcal K}_{n,1-\alpha}\); it proves that coverage and level, if established, cannot be supplemented by the requested uniform root-\(n\) local-power assertion without restricting the geometry of the alternatives.","depends_on":["ass:iid","def:exact-endpoints","def:compatibility-functional","def:primitive-class","def:inference-handle","lem:tie-subexperiment-minimax-boundary","lem:regular-constant-path-power"],"proof_tex":"The specialization constructed in \(\textup{lem:tie-subexperiment-minimax-boundary}\) is contained in \(\overline{\mathcal P}\), and \(P_0\) satisfies \(C_{P_0}(0,0)=0\). Hence any sequence of tests obeying\[\sup_{P:C_P(0,0)=0}E_P[\varphi_n]\le\alpha+o(1)\]also obeys \(E_{P_0}[\varphi_n]\le\alpha+o(1)\). Applying the lower-bound part of \(\textup{lem:tie-subexperiment-minimax-boundary}\), for every \(\eta>0\) there is an alternative \(P_{u_n}\) in that subexperiment such that\[C_{P_{u_n}}(0,0)\asymp c_\eta n^{-2\beta/(4\beta+d)},\qquad E_{P_{u_n}}[\varphi_n]\le\alpha+\eta+o(1).\]The same lemma's second mixture choice produces alternatives satisfying \(C_{P_{u_n}}(0,0)\asymp n^{-1/2}\) and \(E_{P_{u_n}}[\varphi_n]\le\alpha+o(1)\). Thus a positive-mass tie admits root-\(n\) alternatives asymptotically indistinguishable from the null in worst case. Its matching upper-bound calculation shows, within this canonical subexperiment, that the explicit quadratic projection test is consistent whenever\[\frac{C_{P_u}(0,0)}{n^{-2\beta/(4\beta+d)}}\longrightarrow\infty.\]This establishes the asserted sharp boundary only for the stated subexperiment.

For the contrasting constant directions, \(\textup{lem:regular-constant-path-power}\) gives \(C_{P_{u_n}}(0,0)=|\kappa|/\sqrt n\) and a standardized limiting distribution \(N(\kappa/\sigma,1)\), where \(\sigma=\sqrt2(b-a)\). Substituting this value of \(\sigma\) into that lemma's two-sided Gaussian rejection probability gives exactly\[1-\Phi\!\left(z_{1-\alpha/2}-\frac{\kappa}{\sqrt2(b-a)}\right)+\Phi\!\left(-z_{1-\alpha/2}-\frac{\kappa}{\sqrt2(b-a)}\right).\]Hence root-\(n\) separation is regular along these fixed one-dimensional directions even though it fails uniformly over localized positive-mass-tie directions.

If a uniformly valid test had a nontrivial worst-case power curve determined only by \(\sqrt n\,C_P(\theta)\), the root-\(n\) alternatives from the first paragraph would force that curve to exceed its null level at a fixed positive local separation. Their power is instead at most \(\alpha+o(1)\), which is a contradiction. This argument applies to any inversion of the numerical directional-delta procedure only conditionally on that inversion having the claimed uniform level. Nothing in either supporting lemma establishes multiplier critical-value validity, confidence-region coverage, or uniform level for that procedure. The coverage and level questions therefore remain undecided, exactly as stated.","status":"proved"}

